
[1]enallage

   ENAL'LAGE, n. enal'lajy. [Gr. change.]

   A figure, in grammar, by which some change is made in the common mode
   of speech, or when one word is substituted for another; as exercitus
   victor, for victoriousus; scelus, for scelestus.
